<DOC><DOCNO> AP890714-0207 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-07-14-89 2133EST</FILEID><FIRST>r a AM-WeatherpageWeather     07-14 0461</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0480</SECOND><HEAD>Rains Inundate Much of the Nation</HEAD><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   Thunderstorms drenched central Oklahoma, Louisiana and northwestTexas on Friday, forcing people from their houses, flooding anursing home and washing tombstones from cemetery plots.   Most of the streets in Sulphur Springs, Texas, became impassablewhen 1 to 1{ inches fell in about 30 minutes. Some policeencountered water as high as the hoods of their car.   Showers and thunderstorms also continued across much of Oklahomaand northern Texas on Friday. Over 2 inches of rain fell aroundmidday in portions of Payne County, Okla.   In southern Oklahoma, high water from torrential rainstemporarily blocked a highway south of Durant and inundated anursing home in Calera.   The storm dumped 6 inches of rain in the Durant area within a fewhours. In Calera, volunteers sandbagged doors of the Calera Manornursing home after heavy rain sent flood water surging into thelow-lying area.   Before the sandbags were in place, 5 to 6 inches of water floodedmost of the building, officials said. No residents were evacuatedbecause officials feared traveling on the flooded roads would bemore dangerous.   In Louisiana, 8 inches of rain fell in parts of northernLafayette and Vermilion parishes early Friday.   In Opelousas, La., the heavy rain forced at least 100 people outof their homes and moved about a half-dozen tombstones from theircemetery plots.   Thunderstorms were widespread across the Gulf Coast states andthe Florida peninsula. A thunderstorm in the southern suburbs ofBirmingham, Ala., brought almost 1 inch of rain in 40 minutes.   Thunderstorms developed rapidly Friday afternoon over thefoothills of the central and southern Rockies and in southernNebraska.   Showers and thunderstorms also hit parts of New England andeastern New York due to an upper level trough of low pressure.   Skies were mostly sunny west of the Rockies.   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 57degrees at Monterey, Calif., to 112 degrees at Palm Springs, Calif.   The forecast for Saturday called for showers and thunderstormsscattered from the Carolinas across the lower Mississippi Valley tomuch of the Great Lakes; numerous showers and thunderstorms fromKansas across northeast Texas and the central Gulf Coast to northernFlorida; and widely scattered thunderstorms over eastern Washington,Idaho and western Montana.   High temperatures were forecast in the 70s from Nebraska andSouth Dakota across Iowa, the Great Lakes and the upper Ohio Valleyto New England; in the 70s over the Pacific Northwest and along theCalifornia coast; 100 degrees over south central and southwestTexas, southern New Mexico and interior valleys of California;between 100 to 115 degrees in the desert Southwest; and in the 80sand 90s throughout the rest of the nation.</TEXT></DOC>